        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make and chill the meatballs",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine {{lamb-mince}} of lamb mince, the grated onion (squeezed of moisture), {{garlic}} of grated garlic, {{cumin-ground}} of ground cumin, {{coriander-ground}} of ground coriander, {{cinnamon-ground}} of ground cinnamon, {{chilli-flakes}} of chilli flakes, {{parsley-flat}} of parsley, {{mint}} of mint, and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Mix briefly until just combined. Roll into balls about 4 cm across. You should get 16 to 20 meatballs. Place on a tray, cover, and refrigerate for 30 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C fan. Warm {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a small saucepan over medium heat. Cook the second onion for 6 minutes until soft. Add the second measure of garlic and {{cumin-ground}} of cumin; stir for 1 minute. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of hand-crushed tomatoes and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Simmer for 8 minutes. Pour the sauce into a roasting tin. Nestle the meatballs into the sauce in a single layer. Bake for 20 to 25 minutes until the meatballs are cooked through and browning on top. Serve with rice, flatbread, or bulgur wheat.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Squeeze the grated onion in a clean cloth before adding to the mince. Mix only until combined, not longer.",
              "cause": "Onion not squeezed dry, making the mix too wet to bind. Or mix overworked and fat broken down.",
              "symptom": "Meatballs falling apart in the sauce"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use lamb mince with at least 15% fat. Very lean mince makes kafta that tastes more like a health product than a meal.",
              "cause": "Lamb mince too lean.",
              "symptom": "Meatballs dry despite the sauce"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Ground spices lose potency quickly. If the cumin and coriander smell faint in the jar, use 50% more than the recipe states.",
              "cause": "Old spices.",
              "symptom": "Spicing muted and flat"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Kafta (from the Persian word for pounded) is the spiced minced meat mixture that runs through the cooking of the Middle East, Central Asia, and the Indian subcontinent under various names: kofta in India and Pakistan, köfte in Turkey, keftedes in Greece. The Levantine version is lamb-based, heavily herbed, and served with tomato sauce and flatbread. It appears at Lebanese and Syrian family tables as a weekday dinner and at restaurants as part of a mezze spread. It is the kind of dish that tastes more complicated than it is to make.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
